<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910107-0088</DOCNO><DOCID>910107-0088.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Nissan's Move to End Pact   In Britain to Be Contested   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>01/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   NSANY EUROP</CO><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><LP>   LONDON -- Nissan (UK) Ltd., the exclusive Britishdistributor of Nissan autos, said it plans to contest a bidby Nissan Motor Co. of Japan to terminate the distributionagreement.   Nissan (UK) said it will take legal action in Britain, inresponse to Nissan Motor's statement Dec. 27 that it wants tostop its business with the British company. &quot;There are nogrounds on which Nissan Japan can validly terminate thedistribution agreement,&quot; said Nissan (UK), which is owned andmanaged independently from the Japanese company. It said thelegal proceedings will take into account a #250 million($487.4 million) investment made by Nissan (UK) in itsBritish operation, and the market share it has built up.</LP><TEXT>   A spokesman for Nissan Motor in London said the companywants to cut its links with Nissan (UK), because there isn'tany &quot;basis of trust between the two companies anymore.&quot;   Nissan Motor set up the British distribution network in1971 in an effort to generate overseas sales. In recentyears, Nissan Motor has established a production company innorthern England, which is expected to produce 100,000Primera cars this year.   Nissan new-car sales command about a 6% share in Britain.</TEXT></DOC>